## Test Infrastructure

- **Admin test runs hang on exit (recurring).** When `run-coverage.ps1` (full mode) or `native-coverage.ps1` is launched elevated via UAC, the elevated process intermittently fails to exit cleanly after `dotnet test` reports all tests passed — the parent shell sits indefinitely waiting on `Start-Process -Wait`. Same symptom appears with both `Microsoft.CodeCoverage.Console collect` (native script) and the plain coverlet path (managed script). Suspects to investigate:
  - **2026-05-28 confirmed — it is a real hang, not a missed UAC prompt.** The elevated `native-coverage-elevated.ps1` run launched (build + instrument + test-run-start all appeared in the elevated log, so UAC *was* approved), then `dotnet test` never returned within 300s. A watchdog killing the hung `dotnet`/`testhost` to escape produces a CORRUPT cobertura (normally-covered lines show uncovered; `collect` only finalizes on a clean child exit) — so kill-to-recover does not yield a usable report. Pragmatic verification meanwhile: run `scripts/native-coverage.ps1` NON-elevated — branch coverage stays 100%, only USN/admin lines drop; inspect the cobertura per-file to confirm changed lines are covered. See memory `reference_native_coverage_hang.md`. The split-admin-tests item below is the real remedy.
  - `WatchUsnJournal_*` admin tests use `CancelIoEx` to unblock a kernel wait — possible the cancel races with process teardown and leaves a worker thread in a non-signaled wait, blocking the runtime's exit. Worth checking with `procdump -ma` on a hung session to see what threads are alive.
  - `dotnet test` host process (`testhost.dll`) running under instrumentation may not flush the coverage file before the parent reaps it — could be the instrumentation harness, not the tests themselves.
  - A timeout wrapper around the elevated invocation (e.g. `Start-Process` with a watchdog that issues `taskkill /T` after N minutes past the last log line) would at least prevent the session from blocking forever.
  - Long-term: split admin-only tests into a separate test project so the non-admin run stays the default and elevated runs can be opted into with a known-stable test set.

